reviews.review: This movie was definitely a missed opportunity especially given the fact that it was the closing of this 40+ years saga.  Although J.J Abrams was the perfect choice to reintroduce us to the Star Wars universe in the Force Awakens he was clearly the wrong directorial choice for episode IX.  The movie does have great action and visuals but the plot is very convoluted and never makes clear the point or resolves certain characters or dilemmas.  There is entirely way to much fan service in this movie.  Although fan service is not a bad thing in it on its own it has to be measured and context matters.  If anything this movie has solidified that The Last Jedi is the best of these three sequels and I appreciate even more what he was trying to do with his movie.  All in all I didn't hate the movie and there are some redeeming qualities to it however, I found that this movie was more easily digested than the previous two as it contained more empty calories.  I am going to go see it again so hopefully my perspective will change upon a repeat viewing.

I think the movie was really good. It was way more entertaining than the last jedi. I feel the problem is people are overthinking it, when star wars is more of a stupid fun movie. I would recommend it to anyone, it was a lot of fun.

Listen. I had low expectations after the Ryan Johnson disaster that was the last jedi, but set your mind at ease. JJ Abrams has brought star wars back from the brink.
I know the trilogy wasn't the most original piece of cinema, but, I thought the first installment as well as the final installment of the trilogy are solid, entertaining movies. With rise of skywalker as the best of the three movies, and the last jedi as the worst
EXCITING, a great conclusion, there where one or two scenes that meh that's not supposed to be done but the rest was great, really emotional and astonishing plot twist.
Don’t trust the reviews this was a great film.
Pretty average, didn’t really give me the thrills
I enjoy a lot. Included the surprises

It’s a 2 1/2 hour, “I’m sorry” for what we did in The Last Jedi. Plenty of fan service with a very inconsistent story and closes out this trilogy in a very confusing way. Can’t help but think this is Disney begging fans to stay on with the franchise despite the radical direction they’ve taken the franchise.
Very good storytelling and a satisfying close to the saga. Brilliant character development. Will definitely see again.
Aside from some things that could have been explained better or more fleshed out and a bit of a disappointing way for *SPOILER* to go, I loved it immensely. Definitely a satisfying end.
